Class ArchivalUrlRequestParserTest

  • java.lang.Object
    • junit.framework.Assert
      • junit.framework.TestCase
        • org.archive.wayback.archivalurl.ArchivalUrlRequestParserTest
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    junit.framework.Test

    public class ArchivalUrlRequestParserTest
extends junit.framework.TestCase
    Test case for ArchivalUrlRequestParser. This class tests entire ArchivalUrlRequestParser, including its sub-component classes: ReplayRequestParser, PathDatePrefixQueryRequestParser PathDateRangeQueryRequestParser, PathPrefixDatePrefixQueryRequestParser, PathPrefixDateRangeQueryRequestParser and DatelessReplayRequestParser.
    Author:
    Kenji Nagahashi

        public void testDatePathPrefix()

        timestamp without "*", path ending with "*".

        this is interpreted as replay request for the URL including trailing "*". That sounds inconsistent with other cases. (BTW, resultant time-redirect URL has no trailing "*" - there's a special handling happening somewhere.) Should this be interpreted as URL-query for the specific date?

      • testPathDateless

        public void testPathDateless()
                      throws Exception
        test of DatelessReplayRequestParser.

        It also reads Replay/AchorDate from Accept-Date/Accept-Timestamp HTTP headers (Accept-Date is part of Memento protocol). This test is included here, even though it has some Memento-related code, because core part of processing is for Archival-URL.

        One notable difference from with-timestamp request is that WaybackRequest.isBestLatestReplayRequest() is set to true, which used in several places for unclear purpose. This flag is not set in other RequestParser's, even if request is asking for the best latest capture. Probably flag's semantics is slightly different from what its name suggests.

        As this pattern of requests come from URL that escaped Archival-URL rewriting process, it runs extra check on it. Test includes a few negative cases for non-URL paths.

        Throws:
        Exception
